Patriarchal attitudes towards women remain strong and the notion that abortion is a punishable offence is reinforced through societal norms and traditional beliefs (Högberg, Larsson, and Thorsell 2006). Anti-abortion laws in Ethiopia are punitive rather than designed to protect those at risk of becoming pregnant without the capacity to care for or raise a child (Gebre, Naim et al. 2010).
Ethiopia has agreed to uphold implementing laws based on human rights that will protect the freedom of women and girls to have their health needs met (Gebre, Drechsel et al. 2008).
In addition to the restrictive status on abortion, RH services are inequitably available across the country. Although family planning programmes are offered through a wide variety of sources including ethnically divided public health teams, urban locality-based health offices, regional hospitals, and the maternal and child health comprehensive centres in urban areas (FMOH 2005), many men and women are of the opinion that government RH services are lacking. RH services are sometimes stigmatised as ‘abortion-linked services’ and are seen as less available and of inferior quality in rural locations: “There are goods and bads; but here it is cheaper and quicker especially in a city.
